HistoryDaily.com - An Entertaining Look Back  
By Charles Smith and Trevor Smith

January 7, 2003 on this day:

In 1927 the first commercial telephone service across the
Atlantic Ocean became available. The signal was transmitted via
radio waves and calls could only be made between New York and
London. The system was built by AT&T. Not surprisingly, the sound
quality was poor and the weather often interfered. The calls were
also very expensive, costing seventy-five dollars for a
five-minute conversation. Despite these limitations, the system
was a success. Thirty-one calls were placed on the first day.

If you had the premium version you would read more about this
topic. Plus you would read about the first American combat jet.
It was a pretty slick plane despite the fact that it was
primitive by today's standards. There is more in there too!

